04654nam a22006495i 9780228018698DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1378937528  a97802280186987 a10.1515/97802280186982doi  a(DE-B1597)658130  a(OCoLC)1367268174  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN1997.A348bM35 2023 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/722231 aMalakaj, Ervin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAnders als die Andern /cErvin Malakaj. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b34 photos, 3 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aQueer Film Classics ;v700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tSynopsis -- tCredits -- tThe Pleasures and Pains of Watching Anders als die Andern -- tProducing Anders als die Andern Melodrama Between Genre Cinema and Public Health Discourse -- tThe Form of Melodrama Gesture, Anguish, and Queer Life in Anders als die Andern -- tFeeling Backward with Anders als die Andern -- tThe Queer Cinema of Mourning -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReleased in 1919, Anders als die Andern (Different from the Others) stunned audiences with its straightforward depiction of queer love. Supporters celebrated the film’s moving storyline, while conservative detractors succeeded in prohibiting public screenings. Banned and partially destroyed after the rise of Nazism, the film was lost until the 1970s and only about one third of its original footage is preserved today.Directed by Richard Oswald and co-written by Oswald and the renowned sexologist Magnus Hirschfeld, Anders als die Andern is a remarkable artefact of cinema culture connected to the vibrant pre-Stonewall homosexual rights movement of early-twentieth-century Germany. The film makes a strong case for the normalization of homosexuality and for its decriminalization, but the central melodrama still finds its characters undone by their public outing. Ervin Malakaj sees the film’s portrayal of the pain of living life queerly as generating a complex emotional identification in modern spectators, even those living in apparently friendlier circumstances. There is a strange comfort in knowing that we are not alone in our struggles, and Malakaj recuperates Anders als die Andern’s “mournful cinema” as an essential element of its endurance, treating the film’s melancholia as both a valuable feeling in and of itself and as a springboard to engage in an intergenerational queer struggle.Over a century after the film’s release, Anders als die Andern serves as a stark reminder of how hostile the world can be to queer people, but also as an object lesson in how to find sustenance and social connection in tragic narratives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMale homosexuality in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszGermanyxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a1910s.  aRichard Oslwad.  acinema.  acriticism.  agerman film.  aqueer studies.  asexology.  aspectators.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228018698?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228018698423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228018698/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruy